le Cary, Somerset, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England"},"nl":{"Abt 1375–6 January 1409":"circa 1375–6 januari 1409","1375–1409":"1375–1409","1377–1415":"1377–1415","–1420":"–1420","1382–1409":"1382–1409","1402–1491":"1402–1491","1355–1401":"1355–1401","1356–1410":"1356–1410","6 January 1409":"6 januari 1409","15 May 1401":"15 mei 1401","1382":"1382","1491":"1491","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1401":"1401","1356":"1356","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","Abt 1375":"circa 1375","1420":"1420","Abt 1374":"circa 1374","1375":"1375","23 July 1402":"23 juli 1402","1409":"1409","Long Ashton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Long Ashton, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St. Lawrence In Cripplegate Ward, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Westbury, Wiltshire, England":"Westbury, Wiltshire, England","Castle Cary, Somerset, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England"},"en":{"Abt 1375–6 January 1409":"about 1375–6 January 1409","1375–1409":"1375–1409","1377–1415":"1377–1415","–1420":"–1420","1382–1409":"1382–1409","1402–1491":"1402–1491","1355–1401":"1355–1401","1356–1410":"1356–1410","6 January 1409":"6 January 1409","15 May 1401":"15 May 1401","1382":"1382","1491":"1491","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1401":"1401","1356":"1356","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","Abt 1375":"about 1375","1420":"1420","Abt 1374":"about 1374","1375":"1375","23 July 1402":"23 July 1402","1409":"1409","Long Ashton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Long Ashton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","St. Lawrence In Cripplegate Ward, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Westbury, Wiltshire, England":"Westbury, Wiltshire, England","Castle Cary, Somerset, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Saint","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Cyr, Remy.","English and French: nickname for a particularly pious individual, from Old French and Middle English <i>saint(e)</i>, <i>seint(e)</i> ‘holy’ (from Latin <i>sanctus</i> ‘blameless, holy’). The vocabulary word was occasionally used in the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Maur","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ernesto, Ramon, Adela, Carlos, Eladio, Emilia, Estrella, Horacio, Jorge, Jose, Juan, Mario.  Italian Alessandra, Angelo, Cecilio, Cosimo, Gianfranco, Lorenzo, Mauro.","Catalan: from the personal name <i>Mauri</i>, Latin <i>Maurus</i> (see   Mauro  ).","Catalan and French (Occitan): probably from the personal name <i>Malric</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Almaricus</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Mauro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Angelo, Sal, Domenic, Giuseppe, Antonio, Carmine, Carmelo, Domenico, Gaetano, Nino, Pasquale.","Italian (mainly southern): from the personal name <i>Mauro</i>, derived from the Latin personal and ethnic name <i>Maurus</i>, borne by various early Christian saints and meaning ‘Moor, North African’. Compare   Moore   and   Moro  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Saint Maur 6th Baron St Maur was born about 1375, in Castle Cary, Somerset, England, his father, Richard Saint Maur, was 21 and his mother, Ela St. Lo, was 21. He married Mary Peyvre. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 6 January 1409, at the age of 35."},"et":{"Abt 1375–6 January 1409":"umbes 1375–6. jaanuar 1409","1375–1409":"1375–1409","1377–1415":"1377–1415","–1420":"–1420","1382–1409":"1382–1409","1402–1491":"1402–1491","1355–1401":"1355–1401","1356–1410":"1356–1410","6 January 1409":"6. jaanuar 1409","15 May 1401":"15. mai 1401","1382":"1382","1491":"1491","1415":"1415","1402":"1402","1401":"1401","1356":"1356","1410":"1410","1355":"1355","1377":"1377","Abt 1375":"umbes 1375","1420":"1420","Abt 1374":"umbes 1374","1375":"1375","23 July 1402":"23. juuli 1402","1409":"1409","Long Ashton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Long Ashton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St. Lawrence In Cripplegate Ward, London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Westbury, Wiltshire, England":"Westbury, Wiltshire, England","Castle Cary, Somerset, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1375–6 January 1409":"noin 1375–6. tammikuuta 1409","1375–1409":"1375–1409","1377–1415":"1377–1415","–1420":"–1420","1382–1409":"1382–1409","1402–1491":"14